{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}<!-- not listed in the Queensland Place Names --> {{Infobox Australian place | type = protected | name = Beeron National Park | state = qld | iucn_category = II | image = | caption = | image_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|26|1|2|S|151|18|0|E|display=inline,title}} | force_national_map = | relief = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | map_alt = | nearest_town_or_city = [[Mundubbera]] | area = 70.5 | area_footnotes = | established = 2009 | established_footnotes = | visitation_num = | visitation_year = | visitation_footnotes = | managing_authorities = Queensland Parks and Wildlife Service | url = }} '''Beeron National Park''' is a national park at [[Beeron, Queensland|Beeron]] in the [[Wide Bay–Burnett]] region of [[Queensland]], Australia. The 7050-hectare park preserves plant species of high conservation value.<ref name="bnpms">{{cite web |url=http://www.nprsr.qld.gov.au/managing/plans-strategies/statements/beeron.html |title=Beeron National Park Management Statement 2013 |date=11 November 2013 |publisher=Department of National Parks, Recreation, Sport and Racing |accessdate=19 August 2014 }}</ref>
It is part of both the [[North Burnett Region]] and [[South Burnett Region]] local government areas and the [[Brigalow Belt]] bioregion.<ref name="bnpwet">{{cite web |url=http://wetlandinfo.ehp.qld.gov.au/wetlands/facts-maps/national-park-beeron/ |title=Beeron National Park |work=WetlandInfo |publisher=Department of Environment and Heritage Protection |accessdate=19 August 2014 }}</ref> The park lies within the catchment area of the [[Boyne River (Wide Bay–Burnett)|Boyne River]], a tributary of the [[Burnett River]].
Beeron National Park is home to six endemic species and three plants with conservation significance.<ref name="bnpms"/>
In 2010, an extra 7,000 hectares significantly extended the size of the park.<ref name="pepc">{{Cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/03/30/2860304.htm?site=southqld |title=Park expansion prompts call for more rangers |author=Sam Burgess |accessdate=19 August 2014 |date=30 March 2010 |work=ABC Southern Queensland |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation }}</ref> The addition was made possible by the cooperation of two mining companies who relinquished their mining permits.<ref name="bgenp">{{cite web |url=http://media-newswire.com/release_1115426.html |title=Bligh Government Expands National Parks By 60,000 Hectares To Protect Rare Plants And Animals |date=28 March 2010 |publisher=Media-Newswire.com |accessdate=19 August 2014 }}</ref>
South and west of the national park is Allies Creek State Forest. It is undeveloped with no visitor facilities.
