'''Boris Karlovich Stegmann''' (25 December 1898-28 December 1975) was a Russian [[Ornithology|ornithologist]] of German descent who worked on [[zoogeography]].
Stegmann was born in [[Pskov]], Russia. He worked at the Russian Academy of Sciences from 1921 in the ornithology department. He became a research assistant in 1928 and worked on various bird groups. In 1938 he published his ideas on nine avifaunal centres within the Old World.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stegmann, B.|year=1938| chapter=Principes généraux des subdivisions ornitho-geographiques de la region palearctique |title=Faune de l'URSS. Volume I. No. 2|publisher=Acad. Sci. URSS, Moscow-Leningrad}}</ref> This was an influential work in its time. In 1941, his German ancestry led to his removal from work in Russia and deportation to [[Kazakhstan]]. Exiled in central Asia, he continued his research on birds in the region until 1954. In 1964 he published a volume on the birds of the [[Soviet Union]] along with Aleksandr Ivanovich Ivanov. He also worked on molluscs and on the evolution of birds. In 1978 his work on the comparative anatomy of the avian forelimb was published posthumously with a preface by [[Walter Bock]].<ref>{{cite journal| author=Raikow, Robert J. |pages=135–137| title=Review: Relationships of the Superorders Alectoromorphae and Charadromorphae (Aves): A comparative study of the avian hand| journal=Wilson Bulletin| volume=92| issue=1| year=1980|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v092n01/p0131-p0139.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1007/BF01640496|title=Persönliches: Boris Karlowitsch Stegmann 1898-1975 |author=Kumari, Eerik |journal=Journal of Ornithology|volume=117|issue=3|pages=395-396|year=1976|language=German}}</ref>
