[[File:The Isle of Man.svg|thumb|Location of [[Isle of Man]]]]
The [[Isle of Man]] is a self-governing [[crown dependencies|crown dependency]] in the [[Irish Sea]] between [[England]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. The [[head of state]] is [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]], who holds the title of [[Lord of Mann]]. The Lord of Mann is represented by a [[Lieutenant Governor of the Isle of Man|lieutenant governor]]. Foreign relations and defence are the responsibility of the British Government.
The Isle of Man is a low-tax economy with no [[capital gains tax]], [[wealth tax]], [[stamp duty]], or [[inheritance tax]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/iomfinance/tax/directtax.xml|title=Financial Services Sector - Isle of Man. Where You Can.|work=gov.im|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> and a top rate of [[income tax]] of 20%.<ref name=opw>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlinepersonalswatch.com/news/2013/04/interview-with-brian-donegan-director-of-foreign-direct-investment-at-isle-of-man-government-treasur.html |title=Interview With Brian Donegan, Director Of Foreign Investment, Isle Of Man Government |publisher=OnlinePersonalsWatch |date= |accessdate=4 April 2013}}</ref> The rate of [[corporate tax|corporation tax]] is 0% for almost all types of income; the only exceptions are that the profits of banks are taxed at 10%, as is rental (or other) income from land and buildings situated on the Isle of Man.<ref>[http://www.gov.im/treasury/incometax/strategy/viewnews.gov?page=lib/news/treasury/incometax/newassessorofinc.xml&menuid= New Assessor of Income Tax – Isle of Man Government] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930201146/http://www.gov.im/treasury/incometax/strategy/viewnews.gov?page=lib%2Fnews%2Ftreasury%2Fincometax%2Fnewassessorofinc.xml&menuid= |date=2007-09-30 }}</ref><ref>[http://money.independent.co.uk/personal_finance/tax/article349147.ece Forget Monaco: Isle of Man cuts tax to tempt super-rich – Tax, Money – Independent.co.uk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070510060817/http://money.independent.co.uk/personal_finance/tax/article349147.ece |date=2007-05-10 }}</ref>
[[Offshore bank]]ing, manufacturing, and tourism form key sectors of the economy. Agriculture and fishing, once the mainstays of the economy, now make declining contributions to the island's [[Gross Domestic Product]] (GDP).
